<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="224" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,619,645]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bowerbank" authorityYear="1864" box="[328,473,619,645]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Hymedesmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[328,473,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Hymedesmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[489,517,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">H.</emphasis>
) reddish orange 
<emphasis box="[704,773,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">in situ</emphasis>
, with visible circular porefields and oscules. Acanthostyles I partially spined (153–320 × 6–17 µm), acanthostyles II entirely spined (55–150 × 5–15 µm), (aniso)strongyles (128–275 × 2–8 µm), and arcuate chelae (16–25 µm), abundant at the surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="224" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,500,727,754]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
Description (
<figureCitation box="[357,485,727,754]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5A–B</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Thinly encrusting sponge (
<quantity box="[825,966,727,754]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" unit="mm" value="1.1" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.7">0.7–1.5 mm</quantity>
thick) (
<figureCitation box="[1063,1158,727,754]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). The largest individual (IZUA–POR 175) covered an area of 
<quantity box="[582,666,763,790]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" unit="cm" value="640.0">640 cm</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[667,675,763,777]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">2</superScript>
. Surface smooth, completely covered by small, circular porefields (≈ 
<quantity box="[183,248,799,826]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
in diameter). Some oscules scattered on the surface (0.7–3.0 mm diameter, 
<figureCitation box="[1089,1176,799,826]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). Consistency very soft and fragile. Color in life is reddish orange (
<figureCitation box="[636,759,835,862]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5A–B</figureCitation>
), turning to beige when preserved in ethanol.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,423,871,897]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
Skeleton (
<figureCitation box="[318,408,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Ectosomal skeleton with anisostrongyles forming bundles extending from surface to substrate. Porefield skeleton formed by many unitary strongyles in a mesh, organized as a conical structure. Subectosomal canals less than 
<quantity box="[440,529,943,970]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Subectosomal and choanosomal skeletons overlapping, composed of typical hymedesmioid structure, consisting of a basal layer of spongin with acanthostyles I and II erect on the substratum.Acanthostyles I support the ectosome without piercing it. Isochelae form a scattered layer at the surface, with some found in the choanosome. Incubated larvae present in MNRJ 9524 (≈ 300 µm diameter).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,563,1087,1114]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
Spicules (
<figureCitation box="[315,441,1087,1114]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Figs 5D–J</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[457,547,1087,1113]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,239,612,638]" captionText="TABLE 1. Hymedesmia (Hymedesmia) spp. from Peru. Measurements (in µm) of the spicules (n = 30; unless stated otherwise in parentheses), length x thickness [as minimum– mean–maximum (± standard deviation)], distribution and bathymetry (in meters). Roman numerals correspond to size categories of acanthostyles.Abbreviations: Tor. (tornotes), Str. (strongyles), Sbty. (subtylotes), Tyl. (tyles), Sty. (styles), Ac. (arcuate chelae), Sig. (sigmas) and Mstr. (microstrongyles)." pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</emphasis>
[Only 
<typeStatus box="[648,746,1087,1113]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">holotype</typeStatus>
measurements presented here; for additional data see 
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,239,612,638]" captionText="TABLE 1. Hymedesmia (Hymedesmia) spp. from Peru. Measurements (in µm) of the spicules (n = 30; unless stated otherwise in parentheses), length x thickness [as minimum– mean–maximum (± standard deviation)], distribution and bathymetry (in meters). Roman numerals correspond to size categories of acanthostyles.Abbreviations: Tor. (tornotes), Str. (strongyles), Sbty. (subtylotes), Tyl. (tyles), Sty. (styles), Ac. (arcuate chelae), Sig. (sigmas) and Mstr. (microstrongyles)." pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Table 1</tableCitation>
]. Ectosomal anisostrongyles (
<figureCitation box="[504,629,1123,1150]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Figs 5F–H</figureCitation>
), smooth and straight (
<figureCitation box="[887,972,1123,1150]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5F</figureCitation>
), with rounded and mucronate ends (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5G–H</figureCitation>
), 128– 
<emphasis box="[299,362,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">167.9</emphasis>
–186 (± 13.4) × 2.7– 
<emphasis box="[595,630,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">3.8</emphasis>
–5.4 (± 0.6) × 2.7– 
<emphasis box="[842,877,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">3.7</emphasis>
–4.7µm (tyle). Choanosomal acanthostyles I (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
), acerate tips tapering gradually, rounded base, shaft slightly curved, with spines occupying the basal two thirds of its length, spines mostly slightly curved, those of the base larger than those of the shaft, 153– 
<emphasis box="[1221,1284,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">215.6</emphasis>
–283 (± 37.2) × 5– 
<emphasis box="[204,251,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">11.3</emphasis>
–13 (± 1.4) µm. Choanosomal acanthostyles II (
<figureCitation box="[800,888,1267,1294]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
), straight, tapering gradually, mucronate tip and rounded base, spines spread all over, 88– 
<emphasis box="[611,674,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">107.1</emphasis>
–128 (± 8.7) × 5– 
<emphasis box="[871,906,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">8.3</emphasis>
–10 (± 0.9) µm. Arcuate chelae (
<figureCitation box="[1272,1376,1303,1330]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Hymedesmia (H.) humboldti sp. nov. A–B, live specimen (MNRJ 12078); C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, ectosomal tornote; G–H, details of F; I–J, isochelae. Scale bars: A, approx. 2 cm; B, approx. 0.5 cm; C, 200 µm D–F, 100 µm; G–H, 20 µm; I–J, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831779/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Fig. 5I–J</figureCitation>
), one free spatulate ala and two lateral alae semi-fused with the shaft, which is characteristically curved, bow shaped, 19– 
<emphasis box="[193,242,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">21.8</emphasis>
–24 (± 1.3) × 2.8– 
<emphasis box="[446,481,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">2.9</emphasis>
–3.1 (± 0.1) µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1401,1411,1438]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" box="[199,1401,1411,1438]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1411,1437]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Ecology.</emphasis>
The sponge was epibiont on dead cirripeds, bryozoans, and serpulid polychaetes at 
<quantity box="[1239,1324,1411,1438]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" unit="m" value="11.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="9.0">9–13 m</quantity>
depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="224" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1447,1473]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from 
<collectingRegion box="[512,616,1447,1473]" country="Peru" name="Arequipa" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Arequipa</collectingRegion>
and Moquega regions in 
<collectingCountry box="[906,960,1448,1474]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Peru</collectingCountry>
, and from central-northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1271,1332,1447,1473]" name="Chile" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Chile</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion country="Chile" name="Antofagasta" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Antofagasta</collectingRegion>
and Punta Choros), spanning the latitudes 16.84º to 
<geoCoordinate box="[797,894,1483,1509]" degrees="29.24" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" precision="555" value="-29.24">29.24º S</geoCoordinate>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="224" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,1519,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salani &amp; Willenz &amp; Fernandez &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2022" box="[567,678,1519,1545]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Hymedesmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="humboldti">
<emphasis box="[567,678,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">humboldti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, used as a noun in apposition, refers to the Humboldt current flowing north along most of the Chilean and Peruvian coasts, including all the localities the species was recorded from.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="224" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1591,1617]" pageId="7" pageNumber="224">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is quite similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Salani &amp; Willenz &amp; Fernandez &amp; Hajdu, 2022" authorityName="Salani &amp; Willenz &amp; Fernandez &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2022" box="[660,838,1591,1618]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Hymedesmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="7" pageNumber="224" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="peruana" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Hymedesmia">
